=========================================================
REFERENCES IN C++ (INTERVIEW NOTES)
=========================================================

Definition:
A reference is an alias (another name) for an existing variable.

Syntax:

datatype& ref = variable;

Example:

int x = 10;
int& ref = x;

=========================================================
MEMORY REPRESENTATION
=========================================================

int x = 10;
int& ref = x;

ref and x refer to the SAME memory location.

        +-------+
x ----> |  10   |
ref --->+-------+

Address:

cout << &x;      // Same
cout << &ref;    // Same

=========================================================
BASIC EXAMPLE
=========================================================

#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

int main()
{
    int x = 10;

    int& ref = x;

    ref = 20;

    cout << x;      // 20
}

Output:

20

=========================================================
CHARACTERISTICS OF REFERENCES
=========================================================

1. Must be initialized during declaration.
2. Cannot be NULL.
3. Cannot be reseated (cannot refer to another variable).
4. Acts as an alias.
5. Safer than pointers.
6. No reference arithmetic.

=========================================================
MUST INITIALIZE
=========================================================

int& ref;      // ERROR

Reason:
Reference must refer to an existing object.

=========================================================
CANNOT BE REASSIGNED
=========================================================

int a = 10;
int b = 20;

int& ref = a;

ref = b;

This DOES NOT change the reference.

It means:

a = b;

After execution:

a = 20
b = 20

ref still refers to a.

=========================================================
REFERENCE IS AN ALIAS
=========================================================

int x = 10;

int& ref = x;

ref = 100;

Equivalent to:

x = 100;

=========================================================
REFERENCE vs POINTER
=========================================================

Feature             Reference           Pointer
---------------------------------------------------------
Can be NULL         No                  Yes
Initialization      Mandatory           Optional
Can be Reassigned   No                  Yes
Arithmetic          No                  Yes
Dereference (*)     Not Required        Required
Syntax              Easier              More Complex
Safety              Safer               Less Safe

=========================================================
EXAMPLE
=========================================================

int x = 10;

int& ref = x;

int* ptr = &x;

ref = 20;
*ptr = 30;

x becomes:

30

=========================================================
PASS BY VALUE
=========================================================

void increment(int x)
{
    x++;
}

int a = 10;

increment(a);

Output:

10

Reason:
Copy created.

=========================================================
PASS BY REFERENCE
=========================================================

void increment(int& x)
{
    x++;
}

int a = 10;

increment(a);

Output:

11

No copy created.

=========================================================
WHY PASS BY REFERENCE?
=========================================================

1. Avoid copying.
2. Faster for large objects.
3. Allows modification.
4. Better performance.

=========================================================
EXAMPLE
=========================================================

void print(vector<int>& v)
{
}

No copy of vector.

Efficient.

=========================================================
CONST REFERENCE
=========================================================

void print(const string& s)
{
}

Advantages:
• No copy
• Read-only access
• Efficient

This is one of the MOST USED interview patterns.

=========================================================
WHY USE CONST REFERENCE?
=========================================================

Without const:

void print(string s)

Entire string copied.

With const reference:

void print(const string& s)

No copy.

Safer and faster.

=========================================================
REFERENCE AS FUNCTION RETURN
=========================================================

int& get(int arr[], int i)
{
    return arr[i];
}

int arr[5];

get(arr,0) = 100;

Equivalent:

arr[0] = 100;

=========================================================
DANGLING REFERENCE
=========================================================

int& fun()
{
    int x = 10;

    return x;     // WRONG
}

Reason:
x is destroyed after function returns.

Returned reference becomes dangling.

Undefined Behavior.

=========================================================
REFERENCE TO POINTER
=========================================================

int x = 10;

int* ptr = &x;

int*& ref = ptr;

ref = nullptr;

ptr also becomes nullptr.

=========================================================
REFERENCE TO CONST
=========================================================

const int& ref = 10;

Allowed.

Reason:
Compiler creates temporary object.

=========================================================
NORMAL REFERENCE
=========================================================

int& ref = 10;

Compilation Error.

Reason:
Non-const reference cannot bind to temporary objects.

=========================================================
LVALUE REFERENCE
=========================================================

int x = 10;

int& ref = x;

Binds to:

Named objects (lvalues).

=========================================================
RVALUE REFERENCE (C++11)
=========================================================

int&& ref = 10;

Binds to:

Temporary objects (rvalues).

Used in:
• Move Semantics
• Move Constructor
• Perfect Forwarding

=========================================================
MOST ASKED INTERVIEW QUESTIONS
=========================================================

Q1. What is a Reference?

Answer:
A reference is an alias for an existing variable.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q2. Is reference a separate object?

Answer:
No.

It acts as another name for the same object.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q3. Can reference be NULL?

Answer:
No.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q4. Can reference be changed to refer to another variable?

Answer:
No.

References cannot be reseated.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q5. Why references are safer than pointers?

Answer:
• Cannot be NULL
• Must be initialized
• No pointer arithmetic
• Easier syntax

---------------------------------------------------------

Q6. Why use pass by reference?

Answer:
Avoid copying and improve performance.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q7. Why use const reference?

Answer:
Prevents copying and prevents modification.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q8. Can references return from functions?

Answer:
Yes.

But never return references to local variables.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q9. Difference between reference and pointer?

Answer:
Pointer can be null and reseated.
Reference cannot.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q10. Can references bind to temporary objects?

Answer:

int& ref = 10;          // NO
const int& ref = 10;    // YES
int&& ref = 10;         // YES

=========================================================
INTERVIEW READY ANSWER (30 Seconds)
=========================================================

A reference in C++ is an alias for an existing variable. It must be
initialized during declaration and cannot be null or reseated. References
are widely used for pass-by-reference and const-reference to avoid
unnecessary copies and improve performance. They are safer and simpler
than pointers and form the basis for move semantics through rvalue
references introduced in C++11.

